Video: 8 edits ≤30s (6 sport + 2 footwear).

Rights: 6 months; GCC + Egypt + SEA; digital/retail/social only.

Gym Partnerships: Does Under Armour have a gym partner where we can get the athletes for Training ? If yes, what are the locations ?

Content pillars & weekly themes (1× guide): 3–4 thematic lanes mapped to Running/Training/Cycling + lifestyle moments.

One on-ground shooter, Editor in office, AE supporting Producer on ground.

SEPTEMBER: Back to Routine & Fresh Starts

Focus Point 1: Smart & Healthy Lunchbox Hacks

Content Idea 1: "Back to School, Back to Fresh!" carousel featuring healthy and easy-to-prepare lunchbox ideas using Géant's Farm Fresh produce and Classic snacks. 

Content Idea 2: Reel showcasing quick weekday breakfast and lunch recipes for busy parents and students, highlighting convenient Géant products and meal solutions. 

Rationale: Building on the August "Back to School" theme, this focuses on establishing healthy routines for the academic year. It appeals to "Fresh Seekers" and "Community-Minded Shoppers" looking for practical, affordable solutions to keep their families well-fed during busy weekdays. This aligns with the "Relatable & Practical" and "Fresh Start Community Engagement" pillars. 


Focus Point 2: Fall Flavors & Cozy Home Essentials

Content Idea 1: Showcase seasonal produce perfect for comforting autumn meals, like squashes, root vegetables, and baking apples, emphasizing freshness and quality. 

Content Idea 2: Highlight FMCG items for home refreshing and cozy evenings, such as new aroma diffusers, specialty tea blends, and baking ingredients. 

Rationale: As summer officially ends and the weather cools, this focuses on the shift in seasons and creating a comforting home environment. It appeals to "Community Hosts" and "Weekend Explorers" looking to embrace new routines and seasonal comforts, tying into "Seasonal and Thematic Activations." 

Focus Point 3: Wellness & Rejuvenation

Content Idea 1: Feature Géant's health and organic range, including new arrivals or popular items, with tips on incorporating them into daily routines for energy and well-being. 

Content Idea 2: Interactive "Guess the Superfood" or "Healthy Snack Swap" polls on Instagram stories to engage users and educate them on nutritious options available at Géant. 

Rationale: Following the summer break, many people look to reset their health and wellness goals. This caters to "Fresh Seekers" and reinforces Géant's commitment to quality and health, aligning with the "Relatable & Practical" pillar. 


Focus Point 4: Weekday Convenience & Smart Shopping

Content Idea 1: Emphasize Géant's 24/7 stores and home delivery services for hassle-free grocery shopping during busy weekdays. 

Content Idea 2: Short video highlighting "On-the-Go" meal solutions and quick snack ideas for individuals with fast-paced routines, showcasing the convenience and variety. 

Rationale: This directly addresses the "On-the-Go Snackers" and "Afternoon Runners" customer segments by promoting convenience and accessibility, tackling the misconception about Géant's accessibility and reinforcing the "Convenience" value. 


Focus Point 5: Community & Connection

Content Idea 1: User-Generated Content (UGC) challenge: "My Géant Haul for a Fresh Start" encouraging customers to share their September grocery hauls and tag Géant. 

Content Idea 2: Share recipes for communal meals and gatherings, encouraging family and friends to connect over food prepared with Géant's fresh ingredients. 

Rationale: This reinforces Géant's identity as a "Community-Oriented" and "Reliable Best Friend" brand. It leverages "Fresh Start Community Engagement" by encouraging user participation and highlighting how Géant brings people together after the summer holidays. 


Focus Point 6: Everyday Innovation in Store

Content Idea 1: Showcase innovative in-store features like the pineapple cutting machine or specialized counters (e.g., sushi counter, raw honey kiosk) to highlight a unique shopping experience. 

Content Idea 2: Promote exclusive in-store offers or product tastings that encourage physical visits and allow customers to experience Géant's fresh offerings firsthand. 

Rationale: This focuses on the "Everyday Innovation" pillar and "Freshness & Innovation" key focus area , appealing to "Weekend Explorers" and those who value the in-person shopping experience to evaluate fresh produce quality.

Flow + zoning: We should add a simple diagram showing 50/50 retail vs experience within the 8x8, and how people enter/queue/move/exit.

1. Insurance Requirements

    •    Professional Indemnity (E&O): Not applicable—since all content, drafts, and social-media posts are approved by the Client in writing before publication, there is no risk of unapproved errors to insure.
    •    Media Liability & Cyber Insurance: Not applicable—our scope is limited to public account management and content approved by the Client prior to posting; we do not handle sensitive data or require system access that would justify these policies.
⸻
2. Credentials Management & Content Workflow
    •    Secure Vault: All client credentials are stored in Keeper.com, our enterprise-grade password manager. Access is granted only to senior staff and the direct account handlers designated per account—no wider internal sharing.
    •    Rotation & Control:
    •    On any personnel change (including reassignment, departure, or new hires) of team members who have been exposed to client credentials, those credentials are immediately rotated.
    •    Resets and new credential issuance are performed exclusively by the Client’s designated stakeholders—our team cannot modify or reset credentials without your authorization.
    •    Asset Storage & Approval: All creative assets and drafts reside in our secure Dropbox/Google Drive workspace, accessible only to the assigned project team. Every post or campaign is submitted for written Client approval before it goes live.

⸻

With this process:
    1.    Any team member who has ever had access is locked out immediately upon change.
    2.    Only your authorized stakeholders control credential resets.
    3.    We maintain an auditable trail of all rotation events in Keeper.com.

Please let me know if you’d like any further tweaks or if this fully addresses your security needs. Once confirmed, I’ll update the agreement for signature.

As a matter of policy, we don’t provide itemized costs for monthly retainers that bundle multiple services. Our retainers are built intentionally — they reflect the packaged value of combined creative, strategy, and production efforts, with integrated workflows and shared resources.

If we were to break the scope down into isolated, per-deliverable pricing, it would shift the model entirely. Each item would be billed at its standalone rate, without the efficiencies and cost benefits of the packaged structure — resulting in a noticeably higher total.

We structure things this way to stay focused on outcomes, not transactions, and to ensure the best value and flexibility for both sides.

Let me know if you’d like us to walk through the scope and how it maps to your priorities — happy to discuss.

messages.text:
Primary “hook test” windows (most important)
	1.	0:10–0:25 — First “statement” moment (best for your A/B/C hooks)
	2.	1:06–1:21 — Second lift / repeatable section
	3.	2:02–2:17 — Late-song lift (often strongest for saves because it feels “earned”)

Secondary windows (for variety + rehooks)
4) 0:40–0:55 — Verse bar / tension line (good for text-on-screen confessions)
5) 1:36–1:51 — Mid-song pocket (great for “masking / blame” lines + cinematic performance)
6) 2:30–2:45 — Bridge/turnaround energy (ideal for Gallery/paining visuals + match-cuts)
7) 2:50–3:10 — Outro / last hook (great for “Room 01 opens…” countdown edits)

Quick rule so the shoot is efficient

For each window, capture:
	•	1 clean performance take (front, tight close, and 45° profile)
	•	1 “gallery world” take (frame/painting/door-plaque macros)
	•	1 “caught on iPhone” take (grainy intro → cut to clean)

Hi Xavier,

Thanks again for the dialogue on these security and insurance points. To clarify our credential-management process and ensure it meets your requirements, please see the updated language below. I’ve incorporated your note about personnel changes:

1. Insurance Requirements
    •    Workmen’s Compensation: We will maintain statutory Workers’ Compensation insurance as required by law.
    •    Professional Indemnity (E&O): Not applicable—since all content, drafts, and social-media posts are approved by the Client in writing before publication, there is no risk of unapproved errors to insure.
    •    Media Liability & Cyber Insurance: Not applicable—our scope is limited to public account management and content approved by the Client prior to posting; we do not handle sensitive data or require system access that would justify these policies.
⸻
2. Credentials Management & Content Workflow
    •    Secure Vault: All client credentials are stored in Keeper.com, our enterprise-grade password manager. Access is granted only to senior staff and the direct account handlers designated per account—no wider internal sharing.
    •    Rotation & Control:
    •    On any personnel change (including reassignment, departure, or new hires) of team members who have been exposed to client credentials, those credentials are immediately rotated.
    •    Resets and new credential issuance are performed exclusively by the Client’s designated stakeholders—our team cannot modify or reset credentials without your authorization.
    •    Asset Storage & Approval: All creative assets and drafts reside in our secure Dropbox/Google Drive workspace, accessible only to the assigned project team. Every post or campaign is submitted for written Client approval before it goes live.

⸻

With this process:
    1.    Any team member who has ever had access is locked out immediately upon change.
    2.    Only your authorized stakeholders control credential resets.
    3.    We maintain an auditable trail of all rotation events in Keeper.com.

Please let me know if you’d like any further tweaks or if this fully addresses your security needs. Once confirmed, I’ll update the agreement for signature.

Best ,
Molham

Hi Amelia,

As a matter of policy, we don’t provide itemized costs for monthly retainers that bundle multiple services. Our retainers are built intentionally — they reflect the packaged value of combined creative, strategy, and production efforts, with integrated workflows and shared resources.

If we were to break the scope down into isolated, per-deliverable pricing, it would shift the model entirely. Each item would be billed at its standalone rate, without the efficiencies and cost benefits of the packaged structure — resulting in a noticeably higher total.

We structure things this way to stay focused on outcomes, not transactions, and to ensure the best value and flexibility for both sides.

Let me know if you’d like us to walk through the scope and how it maps to your priorities — happy to discuss.

Best,
Molham
